Here is a Delphi code snippet for finding the intersection of two arrays ar1 and ar2:

```
var
  ar1, ar2, intersect: TArray<Integer>;
  i, j, k: Integer;
begin
  // Initialize input arrays
  ar1 := [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];
  ar2 := [2, 4, 6, 8, 10];

  // Initialize output array
  SetLength(intersect, Min(Length(ar1), Length(ar2)));
  k := 0;

  // Loop through arrays and find common elements
  for i := Low(ar1) to High(ar1) do
  begin
    for j := Low(ar2) to High(ar2) do
    begin
      if ar1[i] = ar2[j] then
      begin
        intersect[k] := ar1[i];
        Inc(k);
        Break;
      end;
    end;
  end;

  // Copy the intersection array to a new array with the correct length
  SetLength(intersect, k);

  // Print the intersection array
  for i := Low(intersect) to High(intersect) do
    WriteLn(intersect[i]);
end.
```

In this example, we initialize the input arrays ar1 and ar2 with some sample data. We then create a new array called intersect to store the common elements of ar1 and ar2. We loop through both arrays and compare each element, adding it to the intersect array if it is found in both arrays. Finally, we resize the intersect array to remove any empty space and print its contents.

Note that this implementation has a time complexity of O(n^2), which may not be efficient for large arrays. There are faster algorithms available for finding the intersection of arrays, such as using a hash set or sorting the arrays and performing a merging algorithm.

There are many ways to sort an array in Delphi. Here are a few examples:

1. Using the built-in Sort function:

The fastest and easiest way to sort an array in Delphi is to use the built-in Sort function from the System.Generics.Defaults unit. Here is an example of how you can use this function to sort an array of integers:

```
uses
  System.Generics.Defaults;

var
  myArray: TArray<Integer>;
  comparer: IComparer<Integer>;
begin
  myArray := [3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2, 6, 5];
  comparer := TComparer<Integer>.Default;

  TArray.Sort<Integer>(myArray, comparer);

  // myArray is now sorted
end;
```

In this example, we first initialize an array of integers called `myArray`. We then create an instance of the `IComparer<Integer>` interface using the `TComparer<Integer>.Default` class method, which returns a default comparer for integers. Finally, we call the `TArray.Sort<Integer>` function and pass in the array and the comparer as parameters.

2. Using the Sort method of the TList class:

If you are working with a list of objects instead of an array, you can use the Sort method of the TList class to sort the list. Here is an example:

```
var
  myList: TList<Integer>;
begin
  myList := TList<Integer>.Create;
  myList.Add(3);
  myList.Add(1);
  myList.Add(4);
  myList.Add(1);
  myList.Add(5);
  myList.Add(9);
  myList.Add(2);
  myList.Add(6);
  myList.Add(5);

  myList.Sort;

  // myList is now sorted
end;
```

In this example, we first create a new instance of the TList<Integer> class and add some integers to it. We then call the Sort method of the list to sort the elements.

3. Using the QuickSort algorithm:

If you need to implement your own sorting algorithm for a special case, you can use the QuickSort algorithm. Here is an example of how to do this:

```
procedure QuickSort(var a: array of Integer; low, high: Integer);
var
  i, j, pivot, temp: Integer;
begin
  if low < high then
  begin
    pivot := low;
    i := low;
    j := high;

    while i < j do
    begin
      while (a[i] <= a[pivot]) and (i < high) do
        Inc(i);

      while a[j] > a[pivot] do
        Dec(j);

      if i < j then
      begin
        temp := a[i];
        a[i] := a[j];
        a[j] := temp;
      end;
    end;

    temp := a[pivot];
    a[pivot] := a[j];
    a[j] := temp;

    QuickSort(a, low, j - 1);
    QuickSort(a, j + 1, high);
  end;
end;
```

In this example, we define a new procedure called QuickSort that takes an array of integers `a`, a low index `low`, and a high index `high`. We first check if `low < high` to determine if we need to sort the array. If we do, we choose a pivot element and partition the array into two sub-arrays based on the pivot. We then recursively call the QuickSort procedure on each sub-array until the array is sorted. Note that this is a recursive algorithm and may not be as efficient as other sorting algorithms on large arrays.

