```matlab
% Define the coefficient matrix A and the constant matrix B
A = [2 -3 1; 1 -1 -2; 3 1 -1];
B = [7;-2;0];

% Perform LU factorization
[L, U, P] = lu(A);

% Solve the system using forward and backward substitution
y = forward_substitution(L, P * B);
x = backward_substitution(U, y);

% Display the result
disp('The solution using LU factorization is:');
disp(x);

% Define the function for forward substitution
function y = forward_substitution(L, B)
    n = length(B);
    y = zeros(n, 1);

    for k = 1:n
        y(k) = B(k) - L(k, 1:k-1) * y(1:k-1);
    end
end

% Define the function for backward substitution
function x = backward_substitution(U, y)
    n = length(y);
    x = zeros(n, 1);

    for k = n:-1:1
        x(k) = (y(k) - U(k, k+1:n) * x(k+1:n)) / U(k, k);
    end
end
```

In this code, we first define the coefficient matrix A and the constant matrix B, representing the given system of linear equations. We then perform LU factorization using the built-in Matlab function `lu`, which returns the lower triangular matrix L, the upper triangular matrix U, and the permutation matrix P. Using the obtained matrices, we solve the system via forward and backward substitution.

We define two helper functions, `forward_substitution` and `backward_substitution`, to perform the forward and backward substitution, respectively. The `forward_substitution` function solves the lower triangular system Ly = Pb for the intermediate variable y, while the `backward_substitution` function solves the upper triangular system Ux = y for the final solution x.

