Control Structures:
Control structures define the flow of a program's execution. They can be categorized as Sequential, Selection, and Iteration structures.

Sequential Structure:
Codes are executed line by line in the order they are written. Example:

```java
int x = 10;
int y = 20;
int z = x + y;
System.out.println(z);
```

Blocks:
A block is a group of statements enclosed by curly braces {}. Example:

```java
{
   int x = 15;
   x = x * 2;
}
```

Local Variables:
These are variables declared within a block and are only accessible within that block. Example:

```java
void method() {
    int local = 5;
    System.out.println(local);
}
```

Selection Structures:
These structures allow the program to choose between multiple execution paths based on conditions. They include if, if-else, and switch statements.

The if and if-else Statements:
These branches of a program based on a condition. Example:

```java
int age = 18;

if (age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("You are an adult.");
} else {
    System.out.println("You are a minor.");
}
```

Ternary Operator:
This gives a shortened form of an if-else statement. Example:

```java
int a = 10;
int b = 20;
int max = (a > b) ? a : b;
```

The switch Statement:
Provides multiple paths of execution based on a variable's value. Example:

```java
char grade = 'A';

switch (grade) {
    case 'A':
        System.out.println("Excellent");
        break;
    case 'B':
        System.out.println("Good");
        break;
    case 'C':
        System.out.println("Average");
        break;
    default:
        System.out.println("Invalid grade");
}
```

Iteration Structures:
These structures repeat a block of code based on conditions. They include for, while, and do-while loops.

The for Loop:
Repeats a block of code for a specified number of times. Example:

```java
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    System.out.println("Iteration: " + i);
}
```

The while Loop:
Repeats a block of code as long as a condition is true. Example:

```java
int i = 0;
while (i < 5) {
    System.out.println("Iteration: " + i);
    i++;
}
```

The do-while Loop:
Repeats a block of code at least once and continues as long as a condition is true. Example:

```java
int i = 0;
do {
    System.out.println("Iteration: " + i);
    i++;
} while (i < 5);
```

The continue and break Statements:
'continue' skips the rest of the loop and proceeds to the next iteration. 'break' terminates the loop. Example:

```java
for (int i = 1; i <= 10; i++) {
    if (i % 2 == 0) {
        continue;
    }
    System.out.print(i + " ");
    if (i >= 5) {
        break;
    }
}
```

Infinite Loops:
Loops that never terminate are called infinite loops. Example:

```java
while (true) {
    System.out.println("Infinite loop");
}
```

